Part I - House Rent Prediction¶

by Ben Goodness¶

Introduction¶

This project explores a housing dataset that contains approximately 4700 attributes of house/apartments/flats listing. My aim is to find out what variables has direct impact on the rent increase of house/apartments/flats listings.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

In [2]:
# load in the dataset into a pandas dataframe.
house_rent = pd.read_csv('House_Rent_Dataset.csv', usecols = ['BHK','Rent', 'Size', 'Area Type', 'City',
                                                        'Furnishing Status', 'Tenant Preferred', 'Bathroom', 'Point of Contact'])

columns:¶

  • BHK: Number of Bedrooms, 1 Hall, 1 Kitchen.
  • Rent: Rent of the Houses/Apartments/Flats.
  • Size: Size of the Houses/Apartments/Flats in Square Feet.
  • Area Type: Size of the Houses/Apartments/Flats calculated on either Super Area or Carpet Area or Build Area.
  • City: City where the Houses/Apartments/Flats are Located.
  • Furnishing Status: Furnishing Status of the Houses/Apartments/Flats, either it is Furnished or Semi-Furnished or Unfurnished.
  • Tenant Preferred: Type of Tenant Preferred by the Owner or Agent.
  • Bathroom: Number of Bathrooms.
  • Point of Contact: Whom should you contact for more information regarding the Houses/Apartments/Flats.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

In this Dataset, we have information on 4746 Houses/Apartments/Flats Available for Rent with 9 different parameters like bhk, rent, size, area_type, city, furnishing_status, type of tenant_preferred, No. of bathrooms, point_of_Contact. Most parameters are object type but variables rent and size are datatype int while bhk and bathroom are ordered factor variables with the following levels.

(small) > (big)
bhk: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6
bathroom: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

For this project i'm interested in figuring out what features of the dataset interacts best with rent, in order to identify the primary and secondary cause for price. I'm also interested in figuring out what the most common bhk type.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

From this dataset, i expect Size to have the strongest effect on the rent fees. Some other variable parameters might have an effect on rent, though to a much smaller degree than the main effect of size.

# Plotting boxplot of rent and qualitative variables
def var_boxplot(var):
    column = var
    plt.figure(figsize = [20, 15])
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    
    # LEFT plot: boxplot plot
    plt.subplot(4, 2, 1)
    #Let's return the axes object
    ax1 = sb.boxplot(data=house_rent, x='bhk', y=column, color=base_color);

    # RIGHT plot: box plot
    plt.subplot(4, 2, 2)
    sb.boxplot(data=house_rent, x='bathroom', y=column, color=base_color);
    plt.ylim(ax1.get_ylim()) # set y-axis limits to be same as left plot

    # LEFT plot: boxplot plot
    plt.subplot(4, 2, 3)
    #Let's return the axes object
    ax1 = sb.boxplot(data=house_rent, x='city', y=column, color=base_color);

    # RIGHT plot: box plot
    plt.subplot(4, 2, 4)
    sb.boxplot(data=house_rent, x='tenant_preferred', y=column, color=base_color);
    plt.ylim(ax1.get_ylim()) # set y-axis limits to be same as left plot

    # LEFT plot: boxplot plot
    plt.subplot(4, 2, 5)
    #Let's return the axes object
    ax1 = sb.boxplot(data=house_rent, x='furnishing_status', y=column, color=base_color);

    # RIGHT plot: box plot
    plt.subplot(4, 2, 6)
    sb.boxplot(data=house_rent, x='point_of_contact', y=column, color=base_color)
    plt.ylim(ax1.get_ylim()) # set y-axis limits to be same as left plot

    # LEFT plot: boxplot plot
    plt.subplot(4, 2, 7)
    #Let's return the axes object
    ax1 = sb.boxplot(data=house_rent, x='area_type', y=column, color=base_color)

var_boxplot('rent')

As expected, bhk and bathroom showed similar reactionship, they appear to also have strong correlation towards rent. For bhk and bathroom, rent increases in an ordered manner. Both variables are identical because the number of bhk ddetermines the number of bathroom.
As for other Norminal variables, the parameters of each variable have different reactions to rent. We will only consider variables City, Area Type and Point of Contact because they had their parameters 'mumbai', 'contact agent', and 'Carpet Area' react best to rent with a maximum of above 60,000. While for variable tenant preferred, there wasn't a clear distinction in its distribution. The result was balanced between 'family' and 'bachelors'.

Since we know that price reacts best to rent, lets find out what variable might react to size best?

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Some points showed how the rent increased without the influence of size. We need to find out what features caused this non-linear increase.
I extended my investigation of Rent against house/apartment size in this section by looking at the impact of Bhk(categorical), City, Point of Contact and Area Type the three norminal quality features, to identify the root cause of what features caused non-linear increase of rent. The multivariate exploration here showed that there indeed is a positive effect of City(mumbai), Point of Contact(contact agent) and Area Type(carpet area) on Rent price. This effect tells us that rent inreases for houses/apartment gotten in Mumbai, acquired through Contact Agent and built in Carpet Areas.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Looking back on the point plots, it doesn't seem like there's a systematic interaction effect between the three Norminal features. Interestingly, the plot for Rent against Size and city, every city had a linear increase over Size except for Mumbai.

Conclusions¶

Carrying out our investigation on what effects increase in rent, Size was the most important feature in predicting Rent just as we expected. However, we discovered some points showed a non-linear increase in rent when plotted on a scatter plot of Rent against Size. Our investigation later revealed to us that other features like Bhk, City, Area Type and Point of Contact has positive reaction to Rent and is responsible for the non-linear increase of Rent. Steps were followed in carrying out our investigation:

Firstly, we used univariate exploration to get the overall distribution of all the variables of the datset. We discovered outliers in a histogram graph of Rent which were deleted from the dataset. Also high volume of dats were located at the lower end of the Quantitative and Categorical variables.

Next, we used bivariate exploration. A scatter plot of both Rent and Size showed Us Rent and Size both have a strong positive linear relationship. However, from the scatter plot there were increase in Rent which were non-linear. Further investigation of the categorical and norminal variables were done and bhk, bathroom, city, point of contact and area type reacted to increase in Rent.

Lastly, multivariate exploration was used to explore analysis of the norminal measures of quality and its relationship between rent and size. Here we discovered features in city, aeea_type and point of contact were the three norminal variables responsible for the non-linear increase of rent.
